
-> The ls command with '-l' option shows detailed information about permissions and ownership.

    # ls -l <file-name>

-> Use the ls command '-d' option to show detailed information about a directory itself, and not its contents.

    # ls -ld <directory-name>

-> The first character of the long listing is the file type, and is interpreted as follows:
        
    • - is a regular file.
    • d is a directory.
    • l is a symbolic link.
    • c is a character device file.
    • b is a block device file.
    • p is a named pipe file.
    • s is a local socket file.

-> The next nine characters represent the file permissions. These characters are interpreted as three sets of three characters: The first set are permissions that apply to the file owner. The second set are for the file's group owner. The last set applies to all other (world) users.

-> The ls command with '-a' option shows the permissions of hidden files, including the special files
to represent the directory and its parent.

-> The . special directory reflects the permissions of directory itself, and the .. special directory reflects the permissions of its parent directory.

Relative file permissions:
--------------------------

Who         -> User (u), Group (g), Others (o), and All (a)

Operation   -> add (+), remove (-)

Permission  -> Read (r), Write (w), and Execute (x)

How to change permission:
-------------------------

    # chmod g+w file1.txt -> add write permission to the group of file named file1.txt.

    # chmod g-x file1.txt -> removes executable permission from the group

Absolute file permissions:
--------------------------

    Read    - 4

    Write   - 2

    Execute - 1

How to change the permission:
-----------------------------

    # chmod 755 file1.txt -> for User all(rwx), Group (r-x), and Others (r-x)


How to change the ownership of a file/ directory:
-------------------------------------------------

    Syntax:

    Method 1:
        
        # chown user:group <file/directory-name>

    Method 2:

        # chgrp <group-name> <file/directory>

    Example:

        # chown iwbandara   file1.txt   -> Change the user to iwbandara of file1.txt, no change to the group.

        # chown iwbandara:sysadmin file1.txt    -> Changes the user and the group at the same time.

        # chown :networkengineers file1.txt     -> Changes the group to networkengineers group. 

**** The -R option will be used to recursively do the change.
